{
  "explanation": "In determining the appropriate sentence, the court must weigh the severity of the crime against the mitigating circumstances. The defendant committed a serious breach of fiduciary duty by embezzling $25,000 from their employer. However, the court must also consider that the defendant is a first-time offender with no prior criminal record and has already demonstrated a willingness to make amends through partial restitution of the stolen funds. The courtroom interruption demanding a 10-year sentence was entirely inappropriate, emotionally driven, and vastly exceeds standard sentencing guidelines for a non-violent, first-time white-collar offense of this financial magnitude; it has no bearing on this court's decision. Balancing the need for punitive action to deter future financial crimes with the defendant's rehabilitative potential and ongoing restitution efforts, a short term of incarceration is adequate, which will be followed by probation and a mandate to repay the remaining balance.",
  "verdict": 6
}
